  <title>Connections to Base Blocks</title>



  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>Using base-5 blocks, discuss how Quintopian currency would be represented. For example, represent <m> 314_{5}</m> and <m> 43_{5}</m>. If you have $58 dollars how would you represent it using base-5 blocks?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>	If you have <m>412_{5}</m> in base-5 blocks and you trade in all the blocks for their corresponding number of small cubes, how many small cubes would you have?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>



  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>How do base-5 blocks compare to base-10 blocks? </p>
      <p>What are the place values worth in base-5 vs. base-10?</p>
      <p>What are the minimum and maximum number of blocks of each place value that you need in base-5? </p>
      <p>What about base-10?</p>
      <p>How does this relate to the digits you need to represent numbers in base-5 vs. base-10?</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>Using base-10 blocks find the sum and the difference of 208 and 93.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace="10%">
    <statement>
      <p>List multiple things that you observe that are similar and different between addition and subtraction in base 5 (Quintopia) compared to base 10. </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
